The research outcomes supported by this grant encompass a variety of new results describing homological invariants in commutative algebra and algebraic geometry. They include
(1) in the context of monomial ideals invariant under coordinate permutations, an explicit determination of Castelnuovo-Mumford regularity in the form a solution to an integer optimization problem, and a representation-theoretic description of syzygies via an equivariant version of Hochster's formula;
(2) in the context of determinantal varieties, the calculation of Lyubeznik numbers, Hodge ideals, local Euler obstructions, and other invariants related to the study of local cohomology and D-modules;
(3) the proof of a conjectured relationship by Bruns, Conca and Varbaro, between the 2x2 minors of a generic matrix;
(4) a geometric study of several incarnations of the classical Hermite reciprocity isomorphism from the representation theory of SL_2;
(5) a systematic development of the theory of Koszul modules in the standard and bi-graded setting, with emphasis on their applications to algebraic geometry and geometric group theory.
Several of the research publications supported by this grant have been written jointly with graduate students and postdocs. During the funding period the PI has also co-organized a summer school and several research meetings, as well as a weekly research seminar, and has delivered lecture series aimed at undergraduate and graduate students.					Last Modified: 11/29/2023

